00:52:00.747 --> 00:52:07.706
look something like this. And it works. But we have to write a lot of code. And this is actually

00:52:07.706 --> 00:52:15.227
something that LLMs are really good at, generally. And it's, like, easy to use for this use case.

00:52:16.347 --> 00:52:21.307
And we can just ask it to extract the name and age. And it can reason flexibly about what those

00:52:21.307 --> 00:52:24.666
values are. So, we don't have to write those complicated regular expressions.

00:52:26.986 --> 00:52:31.467
So, here we've just set up a basic chat. This is in prompt to extract the name and age.

00:52:33.227 --> 00:52:37.947
And now when we ask it to extract that from two of those elements in the vector,

00:52:37.947 --> 00:52:44.507
those free text elements, it gives us back a name and age. So, this is great. But this is still just

00:52:44.507 --> 00:52:50.187
free text. It would probably be better if we could get it into some kind of R object,

00:52:50.986 --> 00:53:00.747
like a list or a data frame. So, something like this, where you have a list with the name and the

00:53:00.747 --> 00:53:10.027
age, like an object that we're used to working with in R. And you can pretty easily do this

00:53:10.027 --> 00:53:16.426
with Elmer with the chat structured function or method. So, this returns a piece of structured

00:53:16.426 --> 00:53:23.067
data instead of just free text. The trick is that we first have to tell it what structure we want.

00:53:24.426 --> 00:53:34.266
