particular questions about getting this going. Okay. So,

01:07:36.587 --> 01:07:41.947
in general, if you're trying to get an LLM to do what you want it to do,

01:07:41.947 --> 01:07:47.067
sometimes it's just not possible to get it to fully do what you want it to do. But to start,

01:07:47.067 --> 01:07:52.107
you might ask yourself three questions, which is, one, do you use the best model or the best model

01:07:52.107 --> 01:08:00.107
for your use case? And if not, try using a better or more recent model, because they really can

01:08:00.107 --> 01:08:06.107
vary a lot. In the prompt, did you really clearly explain what you want the model to do?

01:08:06.107 --> 01:08:11.227
And into this process,

01:08:11.827 --> 01:08:21.827
is very similar in many ways to explaining how to do something to another person or documenting a process.

01:08:22.403 --> 01:08:25.043
And so you can kind of evaluate if you clearly explained,

01:08:25.043 --> 01:08:26.803
in much the same way as you would evaluate

01:08:26.803 --> 01:08:29.083
if you clearly explained to another person.

01:08:36.443 --> 01:08:38.482
And then the third question is,

01:08:38.482 --> 01:08:40.803
did you provide examples of what you want?

01:08:40.803 --> 01:08:43.643
Generally, it's very helpful to add examples

01:08:43.643 --> 01:08:45.402
into the system prompt.

01:08:48.723 --> 01:08:50.603
Okay, if you've done those three things

01:08:50.603 --> 01:08:54.603
and it is still not doing what you want,

01:08:55.723 --> 01:08:57.962
you might need to look into something else

01:08:57.962 --> 01:09:00.003
or it might not be really possible

01:09:00.003 --> 01:09:02.203
to get it to perform as you want it to do.

01:09:03.162 --> 01:09:06.043
Okay, but these, if you answer these three questions,

01:09:06.043 --> 01:09:07.003
you've done these three things,

01:09:07.003 --> 01:09:09.083
that can really help a lot

01:09:09.083 --> 01:09:11.843
and take care of a lot of the sort of model misbehaving

01:09:11.843 --> 01:09:13.162
that people often see.

01:09:15.634 --> 01:09:22.794
Okay, and you might ask, like, what you should put in the system prompt versus

01:09:22.794 --> 01:09:29.034
the user prompt, meaning, like, the prompt that you're sending to the model, you

01:09:29.034 --> 01:09:33.273
know, each time you send a request. And the short answer is that if you have any

01:09:33.273 --> 01:09:37.994
instructions or background knowledge, put that in the system prompt. This is going

01:09:37.994 --> 01:09:42.674
to be something that guides the entire conversation, and so you want to put that

01:09:42.674 --> 01:09:47.233
in the system prompt. You don't have to send it each time. Okay, a couple other

01:09:47.233 --> 01:09:51.474
tips. You can use LLMs to help you draft or improve your prompts. Cloud is a prompt

01:09:51.474 --> 01:09:58.514
generator. This can generally be helpful if you're new to prompt writing. Structure

01:09:58.514 --> 01:10:03.154
is also really helpful. Again, this is not that different from, you know, writing a

01:10:03.154 --> 01:10:09.794
set of instructions for another person. So you can use markdown headings or XML tags

01:10:09.794 --> 01:10:17.634
to give structure to your prompts. You can also use variables to insert dynamic

01:10:17.634 --> 01:10:23.473
content into your prompt. So, for example, like, if you have content in another file

01:10:23.473 --> 01:10:28.193
where that file is changing or you want to conditionally read something, you can use

01:10:28.193 --> 01:10:32.994
variables. You do need to be aware of something called prompt injection, which is

01:10:32.994 --> 01:10:37.714
where you could insert malicious information into a prompt, get the LLM to do stuff you

01:10:37.714 --> 01:10:42.034
don't want. In general, you want to make sure you're doing this with files that you

01:10:42.034 --> 01:10:48.994
trust and have, you know, verified do not have anything malicious in them. And you often

01:10:48.994 --> 01:10:59.794
generally need to be aware of what files your LLM has access to. Okay. A couple other tips.

01:10:59.794 --> 01:11:04.193
Like I said, generally you want to get prompts out of your code and into separate files.

01:11:04.193 --> 01:11:10.034
This is easier for you to read. It's easier to read diffs if you're using version control.

01:11:10.034 --> 01:11:13.394
It's easier to organize. It might not make that much difference with the LLM, but it's

01:11:13.394 --> 01:11:16.913
going to make a difference for you as the person and anyone you're collaborating with.

01:11:20.273 --> 01:11:24.033
It can also be really helpful to force the model to say things out loud.

01:11:25.553 --> 01:11:29.393
We're going to talk about tool calling in a bit, but you might only want it to do three

01:11:29.393 --> 01:11:35.313
rounds of that. And if you force it to say that out loud to itself or to add it in a memo to

01:11:35.313 --> 01:11:40.833
itself, it's sort of like its internal monologue, it can help it actually obey the rules that you're

01:11:40.833 --> 01:11:48.273
telling it to obey. On the Elmer website, there's a vignette about prompt design.

01:11:49.794 --> 01:11:55.234
And this is really helpful if you're thinking about running prompt. So, I encourage you to

01:11:55.234 --> 01:12:00.113
take a look at that. Okay.

01:12:11.234 --> 01:12:16.514
Okay. Any questions about prompt writing?

01:12:16.514 --> 01:12:28.833
Cool. So, now we're going to talk about tool calling.

01:12:30.594 --> 01:12:37.234
And we just saw how to add knowledge with prompting. And so, now we're going to talk

01:12:37.234 --> 01:12:44.033
about how to add abilities with tools. And this is another way to make LLMs useful for you.

01:12:44.033 --> 01:12:49.553
So, prompting is generally for adding knowledge. Tools are for adding abilities that LLMs don't

01:12:49.553 --> 01:12:57.154
have out of the box. So, before we talk about tool calling, we're going to take a look at how LLMs

01:12:57.154 --> 01:13:03.234
actually work and clarify what they actually can and can't do because it can be a little confusing.

01:13:04.673 --> 01:13:12.354
So, on their own, do you think LLMs can access the internet, run code, or send an email?

01:13:13.313 --> 01:13:20.273
We can try it out. Here's a chat where we're just asking Claude Haiku what the weather is like.

01:13:20.913 --> 01:13:24.193
I think the implication is that right now in San Francisco.

01:13:27.634 --> 01:13:31.313
And we're going to get a response where it basically says, I don't have access to that,

01:13:31.313 --> 01:13:36.354
and I can't tell you. And that's because LLMs don't actually have access to real time data.

01:13:37.473 --> 01:13:41.873
They don't have a built in internet connection. They were trained up until a particular

01:13:41.873 --> 01:13:46.834
date, and that is the boundary of their knowledge. And anything past that, they don't know about.

01:13:49.153 --> 01:13:53.313
And what about doing something to affect the world, like writing a file to your computer?

01:13:54.114 --> 01:14:00.674
So, what if we ask it to write a data frame to a CSV file? Again, it's going to say, I can't

01:14:00.674 --> 01:14:08.834
really do that. Because LLMs can't affect the world. They can't change your environment or

01:14:08.834 --> 01:14:14.834
any environment. And at this point, you might be thinking, like, this can't possibly be true.

01:14:14.834 --> 01:14:19.313
I know that these things can do it. I'm told they can do everything for me. And you're saying they

01:14:19.313 --> 01:14:25.873
can't even tell me the current weather. And the distinction is that on their own, LLMs cannot do

01:14:25.873 --> 01:14:30.674
this. But they can if you give them the right tools. So, we're going to see how to do that

01:14:30.674 --> 01:14:38.193
with Elmer. A tool is essentially a function and metadata. And if you've ever written in

01:14:38.193 --> 01:14:42.193
R function and then documented it, this is basically the same thing. If you've written

01:14:42.193 --> 01:14:47.634
in R function and written documentation, you can write a tool. It's basically the same process,

01:14:47.634 --> 01:14:51.634
just with an LLM as the intended audience instead of another person.

01:14:54.114 --> 01:15:00.193
Okay. So, we can use tools to do things like bring real time or up-to-date information to the model

01:15:00.993 --> 01:15:03.153
or let the model interact with the world.

01:15:04.114 --> 01:15:07.153
So, we're going to see how to implement tools in R with Elmer.

01:15:09.554 --> 01:15:14.993
I'm going to go over this at a high level, and then we'll take a closer look at the specifics

01:15:14.993 --> 01:15:20.354
of how to do this. So, the first step is just to write or find an R function that

01:15:20.354 --> 01:15:23.074
carries out your desired functionality.

01:15:23.713 --> 01:15:30.433
So, let's say we want to make a tool so that the LLM can access information about the current

01:15:30.433 --> 01:15:34.913
weather. We can write a function get weather. We would have some code in there that returns

01:15:34.913 --> 01:15:43.473
the weather for latitude and longitude. And then the second step is to document that function

01:15:44.433 --> 01:15:51.313
for the LLM. In Elmer, you do this with the tool function, and we pass it the name of the

