02:04:22.932 --> 02:04:31.932
And so, first, we talked about this a little bit, but there's another sort of distinction between model providers and LLMs that I want to draw out.

02:04:31.932 --> 02:04:34.932
So, again, the provider is the company that hosts the model.

02:04:34.932 --> 02:04:38.932
The LLM is the actual model that generates responses to your queries.

02:04:38.932 --> 02:04:41.932
So, like we keep saying, LLMs are stateless.

02:04:41.932 --> 02:04:44.932
They have no memory of your prior requests.

02:04:44.932 --> 02:04:49.932
And this means that the LLM itself, the actual model, is not remembering anything.

02:04:49.932 --> 02:04:52.932
If you send it your data, it does not remember your data.

02:04:52.932 --> 02:04:55.932
It doesn't remember your requests.

02:04:55.932 --> 02:05:01.932
It doesn't have, like, a memory portion of the model that is storing this.

02:05:01.932 --> 02:05:05.932
At least the core LLM technology does not have this.

02:05:05.932 --> 02:05:16.932
The tricky part is that the model provider itself might store your requests or might log them and then store them.

02:05:16.932 --> 02:05:23.932
And so, the takeaway is that the model, even if the model doesn't remember you, the model provider's servers might.

02:05:23.932 --> 02:05:33.932
And so, this is where, yeah, data privacy, issues with protected data, all of that can come in.

