02:05:51.932 --> 02:05:52.932
You don't know what happens there.

02:05:52.932 --> 02:05:54.932
You send it to Anthropic.

02:05:54.932 --> 02:05:57.932
Anthropic sends you a response back.

02:05:58.932 --> 02:06:03.932
But on Anthropic's side or the model provider's side, it's taking that.

02:06:03.932 --> 02:06:04.932
It took your request.

02:06:04.932 --> 02:06:06.932
It sent it to its model.

02:06:06.932 --> 02:06:09.932
It's routing it to the actual LLM.

02:06:09.932 --> 02:06:12.932
And, again, it's stateless.

02:06:12.932 --> 02:06:15.932
No data is stored there.

02:06:15.932 --> 02:06:18.932
LLM gives a model provider response.

02:06:18.932 --> 02:06:21.932
The model provider sends it back to you.

02:06:21.932 --> 02:06:25.932
The nuance is that, again, the model provider might store your data.

02:06:25.932 --> 02:06:29.932
So, it could store your data and use it for future model training.

02:06:29.932 --> 02:06:32.932
It could maybe share it with third parties.

02:06:32.932 --> 02:06:36.932
And it might just store it to have it.

02:06:36.932 --> 02:06:44.932
And this can vary by provider and by your agreement with your provider.

02:06:44.932 --> 02:06:46.932
Okay.

02:06:46.932 --> 02:06:51.932
And so, this, again, changes a little bit when you are using something like a

02:06:51.932 --> 02:06:54.932
coding agent because there's more inputs that can go into it.

02:06:54.932 --> 02:06:57.932
Like I said, like Posit Assistant can see your R and Python session.

02:06:57.932 --> 02:06:59.932
It can also see your console.

02:06:59.932 --> 02:07:01.932
It can see your files.

02:07:01.932 --> 02:07:03.932
So, all this is going into Posit Assistant.

02:07:03.932 --> 02:07:05.932
And so, then the question is, like, what happens?

02:07:05.932 --> 02:07:10.932
Does that mean, like, you know, Anthropic knows all my files or something

02:07:10.932 --> 02:07:11.932
like that?

02:07:11.932 --> 02:07:13.932
Or does Posit know all my files?

02:07:13.932 --> 02:07:14.932
So, the flow of information is the same.

02:07:14.932 --> 02:07:16.932
Again, the LLM doesn't store your data.

02:07:16.932 --> 02:07:18.932
The model provider might.

02:07:18.932 --> 02:07:23.932
With Posit Assistant, specifically, if you're using the Posit AI service

02:07:23.932 --> 02:07:28.932
in an Anthropic model, we have a ZDR, a zero data retention agreement

02:07:28.932 --> 02:07:31.932
with them, which means they're never going to store.

02:07:31.932 --> 02:07:33.932
They don't store your data.

02:07:33.932 --> 02:07:38.932
And the only reason that Posit would store your data is if you're using

02:07:38.932 --> 02:07:44.932
Posit AI, like you bought Posit AI service and you opted in.

02:07:44.932 --> 02:07:49.932
If those things aren't true, your data would not be stored.

02:07:50.932 --> 02:07:54.932
And we're talking, I'm talking specifically about Posit Assistant here,

02:07:54.932 --> 02:07:57.932
but there might be something similar with whatever coding agent you have

02:07:57.932 --> 02:08:00.932
and whatever model provider you might have.

02:08:00.932 --> 02:08:04.932
But I think the main takeaway is that the LLM doesn't store your data,

02:08:04.932 --> 02:08:07.932
but the model provider might, and you should know what your model provider

02:08:07.932 --> 02:08:11.932
is doing with your data.

02:08:11.932 --> 02:08:16.932
And so, because of that, you, or more likely your organization,

02:08:16.932 --> 02:08:20.932
needs to trust your model provider, and that trust might be formed

02:08:20.932 --> 02:08:24.932
by a formal agreement that you have with the model provider.

02:08:24.932 --> 02:08:27.932
Because you need to know, or your organization at least,

02:08:27.932 --> 02:08:34.932
needs to know what your model provider does with your data.

02:08:34.932 --> 02:08:37.932
And just to clarify, like Elmer, QueryChat, ShinyChat,

02:08:37.932 --> 02:08:41.932
any of those packages, they will never store your data anywhere.

02:08:41.932 --> 02:08:45.932
They just pass the request onto the model provider.

02:08:45.932 --> 02:08:50.932
And, again, Posit Assistant would only store your data if Posit's

02:08:50.932 --> 02:08:54.932
your model provider and you've opted in.

02:08:54.932 --> 02:08:59.932
Okay, so I feel like this sounds bad, or like, you know,

02:08:59.932 --> 02:09:02.932
how can you develop this trust relationship?

02:09:02.932 --> 02:09:05.932
The good news is that this is actually relatively easy

02:09:05.932 --> 02:09:09.932
for organizations to do.

02:09:09.932 --> 02:09:12.932
ZDRs or HIPAA-compliant agreements or other arrangements,

02:09:12.932 --> 02:09:15.932
depending on the level of protection you need for your data,

02:09:15.932 --> 02:09:19.932
are pretty common with model providers now.

02:09:19.932 --> 02:09:21.932
And this would be something that your organization,

02:09:21.932 --> 02:09:24.932
like your compliance team or something, would probably work out

02:09:24.932 --> 02:09:27.932
with the model provider, like not you as an individual.

02:09:27.932 --> 02:09:29.932
And then they would tell you what agreement you have in place,

02:09:29.932 --> 02:09:35.932
what data you can use with the models, all of that.

02:09:35.932 --> 02:09:40.932
Here's a blog post if you want to learn more about that.

